## Proposed Books
* [Tidy Modeling with R](https://www.tmwr.org/index.html)
  * Book is still being written but is mostly complete (2021-02)
  * No exercises.
* [An Introduction to Spatial Data Analysis and Visualisation in R](https://spatialanalysisonline.com/An%20Introduction%20to%20Spatial%20Data%20Analysis%20in%20R.pdf)
  * Very narrow subject area.
  * A lot of R code.
  * No exercises.
* [Geocomputation with R](https://geocompr.robinlovelace.net/)
  * Very narrow subject area.
  * A lot of R code.
  * Has exercises.
* Forecasting: Principles and Practice](https://otexts.com/fpp2/)
  * Upper level stats textbook. 
  * Limited R examples but it show you how to do forecasting in R.
  * Standard level of math for a forcasting textbook.
* [Bayes Rules! An Introduction to Bayesian Modeling with R](https://www.bayesrulesbook.com/)
  * People would need a solid background in probability.
  * Lots of R code.
  * Has exercises.
  * The last two chapters are not online.
* [An Introduction to Bayesian Thinking](https://statswithr.github.io/book/)
  * A fairly gentle introduction to Bayes. Would only require a bit of stats background.
  * Only the intro chapter has exercises.
* [Fundamentals of Data Visualization](https://clauswilke.com/dataviz/index.html)
  * Covers a lot of different plots.
  * The plots look like they come from R but there is no R code.
  * May have R code in a git repo.
* [Reasoning with Data: An Introduction to Traditional and Bayesian Statistics Using R](https://www.amazon.com/dp/1462530265)
  * No online version but it is inexpensive.
  * Very gentle introduction to the topic.
  * Has exercises.
  * Uses R.
* [Modeling Techniques in Predictive Analytics with Python and R](https://www.amazon.com/dp/9353065739/)
  * Works through different models
  * Kind of dated (2014), maybe old school R
  * Intro level of modelling


